description:
Sprinkled liberally in amongst some of the poppy patches in the western Antelope Valley.  Unfortunately not quite open all the way yet, so the petals aren't spread out flat and the stamens aren't unrolled.  But I think that's the style projecting at ~7:00.

I think  this is Gilia tricolor -- comments or corrections welcome.   Does that occur here?   Not supposed to -- not listed in Jepson Mohave bioregion, & no herbarium specimens from there, but it does occur right up to the edge of the Tehatchapis, and this year did have exceptionally good wildflower conditions.  Plus I know I've seen plenty of cases where the bioregion distrib is missing places the plant occurs (e.g., Miniature Lupine here in the Antelope Valley).  EDIT: Yes, herbarium specimens now include all of the S CA counties.

Growth habit shot below; click through to view larger.  There's definitely a little bit of yellow in the tube, though it's hard to see.  Stem is erect, so I think that is supposed to rule out P. minor.  G. leptantha might still be possible, and latiflora is in the running & is certainly more common (though I think the basal leaves here are narrower & lacier).

description: Had never seen anything like this before, so I grabbed some quick shots. But figured it looked too weedy to be native. Right about that: turns out to be an ornamental, native to Argentina, naturalized in the Southwest US. It was growing roadside in a bleak, infrastructure-type dead end right off the freeway. Don't quite remember exactly where; haven't been able to relocate the spot on Google Maps -- I suspect it's changed too much to be recognizable. But it had to be somewhere around Castaic, because that's where I got off I-5 for the first part of my wildflowering mission: took the Old Ridge Route parallel with I-5 to the next exit, Templin Hwy, & got back on the freeway there. Couldn't find it -- or anything like it -- in any of my field guides, although I was pretty sure it was in family Fabaceae. Not common -- as of Jan 09, there was only a single herbarium specimen from Los Angeles County. (See ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_county_map.pl?taxon_id=16... -- county dots are clickable.) Also explains why I didn't succeed in IDing it via a search of the Jepson Manual for Fabaceae in Western Transverse Ranges (not used to the brute force method failing!). Turns out that as of that writing it had been documented only in the Central Valley: ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_JM_treatment.pl?3691,3879.... Finally got it via a Google Images search for "Fabaceae red stamens"! I remembered learning that there are three very different-looking subfamilies within Fabaceae: the pea-like flowers, the mimosa-like, & an oddball 3rd kind. This is the 3rd kind. But it turns out that modern DNA analysis has shown that it's not actually a distinct subfamily; instead it's an ancestral type: loco.biosci.arizona.edu/astragalus/images/phylogenies/fab...
place_guess: Castaic, California, United States
